is a Quarto document that's like an example blog post. So we're going to try and build

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:15.919
one of these landing pages for the blog that gives us links to all these posts.

00:01:16.959 --> 00:01:20.879
So how are we going to do that? The first thing we're going to do is create a new page. This is

00:01:20.879 --> 00:01:26.720
going to be the blog landing page. So I'm going to create a new file. I want it to be a Quarto

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:34.800
document, and I'm going to add the title here. It's just going to be blog. Now I'm going to save that.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:39.440
Where am I going to save it? I'm going to save it inside that blog directory, and I'm going to call

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:45.919
it index.qmd. So remember that means that people will navigate to this page by going to our website,

00:01:45.919 --> 00:01:51.279
and then they'll say blog forward slash, and they should get to this page. Okay, so I've saved it.

00:01:51.279 --> 00:01:56.400
I'm going to render that just so we can have a quick look. Right there is a blog page now that

00:01:56.400 --> 00:02:01.919
exists on my website. It's got nothing on it. The first thing I'm going to do though, before I put

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:08.000
any content here, so I'm going to go back to underscore dot yaml where you know that we can

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:15.360
add items to our navigation, and over in my nav bar, after my link to talks, I'm going to add a link

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:22.880
to the blog directory index.qmd. I'm going to save that, and we should now see that in our

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:28.800
navigation we have that link to the blog page. So we've got this blog page as part of our site.

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:34.160
People can find it. There's just nothing on it. So let me show you how easy it is to add one of

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:39.679
these listings to a Quarto web page. It's as simple as adding another item to the document.

00:02:39.679 --> 00:02:47.360
Yaml, listing, and I'm going to say default. Basically I'm going to provide no options to that

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:53.919
listing, and I'm going to regenerate the page, and almost by magic, I'm actually going to go over to

00:02:53.919 --> 00:03:00.639
Safari so you can see this, like almost by magic we now have a blog. So the listing here, I've just

00:03:00.639 --> 00:03:05.600
used all the default settings. What that means is Quarto is going to look in the directory that this

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:11.119
particular page is in. So it's inside the blog directory. It's going to look for any other

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:16.479
Quarto documents in there, and it's going to create a list of all those documents automatically. So

00:03:16.479 --> 00:03:22.080
it's looking inside those documents for their titles and their descriptions, and it's generating

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:29.199
this list of blog posts. So that's what a listing is. It's a list of other content,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:35.360
and you can see you get this kind of nice default automatic styling. Okay, so what I want to show

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:39.360
you a couple of the options you have when you create a listing. So I'm going to now sort of

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:45.279
deviate from the defaults. So I'm going to add some sub options to the listings option here,

00:03:45.279 --> 00:03:50.639
and the first one I want to show you is one called contents, and this is where Quarto should look

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:55.600
for the things that go in this listing. And when I did that default setting, it was sort of

00:03:55.600 --> 00:04:00.800
equivalent to saying, hey look in this directory, and you can say that with just a slash. If this

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:06.320
file, this blog landing page, had existed sort of one level up at the top level of my directory,

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:10.479
I would have been able to say, hey look in the blog directory for this content.

00:04:11.839 --> 00:04:16.559
The other really important argument to listings is the type of listing you want,

00:04:17.119 --> 00:04:21.839
and the type we're looking at here is just the default type. There's another one called grid,

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:27.440
so let me switch to the grid type, regenerate it, and then I'll show you that over in Zarafari.

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:31.920
It sort of gives you more like these little rectangular tiles that get laid out in a grid.

00:04:32.559 --> 00:04:37.679
So that's another variation, and then there's another built-in type called table,

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:45.200
and that sort of literally gives you a table of this content. So they're the three built-in types

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:52.399
that give you quite a lot of flexibility. So to sort of sum up what a listing is, a listing is an

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:56.880
automatically generated list of content. You didn't have to do any work to create that list,

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:03.200
you just had to tell Kordo where to look for this content. It's styled via a template, so we saw

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:08.720
that you could say type just default, and you get kind of like a blog style listing. Type grid gives

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:14.239
you this grid layout, and then type table is very literally a table of all these links. And a

00:05:14.239 --> 00:05:20.000
listing in Kordo can be included on any page, so you just create the page and then add that listing

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.279
item to the YAML, and you get a listing. And the way that Kordo does this, the way that it's

00:05:25.279 --> 00:05:29.440
generating the links on that listing page, is it actually goes in and looks at those files and

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:36.559
looks at the front matter of them. So in those files, in that blog directory, those Kordo files

00:05:36.559 --> 00:05:43.040
have things like the title set, the description set, the author set, an image set in that YAML,

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:48.720
so that Kordo can generate that nice little link to the content. And you might be asking why

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:53.279
would you want to use a listing? Listings are really great when you've got a very large collection

00:05:53.279 --> 00:05:58.000
of content, so you don't want to sort of by hand create links to all these things. They're also

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.040
really good for things that grow, collections or lists that grow. So if you've got something like a

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:07.519
list of projects that you're adding to over time, a listing makes a lot of sense because you can set

00:06:07.519 --> 00:06:12.320
it up once, and then it's just a matter of adding in the content when you want to expand that list.

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:16.880
So what you've seen is a listing is something that's really common with blogs. You'll see them

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:22.399
out there a lot where people list, it's like a list of blog posts. But listings can be really

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:26.640
useful for other kinds of lists. So I'm going to show you a few examples. Here's an example

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:34.480
on Isabella Velasquez's homepage where she's using a listing to list out her projects, so sort of

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:40.720
like a project portfolio. Here's another example, this is from Megan Hall, and this is a listing of

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:48.239
talks. So rather than sort of creating the talks list by hand, each one of these is a piece of

00:06:48.239 --> 00:06:53.760
content that has a little bit more details if you click on it, but the listing is being used to

00:06:53.760 --> 00:07:00.320
lay out that list of talks. And then here's another one from Mikhail Kanui, which is a listing of

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:04.480
publication. So if you're in the academic sector, this is something you often need to have. And each

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:10.000
one of these listings is actually a link to a published paper on a publisher's website.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.359
There's lots of different uses for listings that go beyond blogs. One of the things that's really

00:07:15.359 --> 00:07:21.519
useful with listings is that you don't have to provide individual pages of content to create a

00:07:21.519 --> 00:07:26.799
listing. So let me show you another way you can do listings. I'm going to go back to the RStudio

00:07:26.799 --> 00:07:33.839
project, and there's another example of a listing that's already in this template, and it's under

00:07:33.839 --> 00:07:39.839
this projects folder. I'm going to have a look at index.qmd, and the first thing I'm going to do is

00:07:39.839 --> 00:07:44.399
I'm just going to render this, just so you can see it. So this file, this page, has been there the

00:07:44.399 --> 00:07:47.839
whole time. We've just never had it in our navigation, so you probably haven't seen it.

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:55.600
Let me pop that open a bit bigger. So this is an example of like a project portfolio type page,

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:59.839
right? I've got this page called projects, and then there's currently just three things on it.

00:07:59.839 --> 00:08:06.399
They've got a title, and a little bit of a description, and some categories that go along

00:08:06.399 --> 00:08:11.519
with them. Now the interesting thing about this particular example is that if you look at the way

00:08:11.519 --> 00:08:16.880
the listing is set up, the contents isn't a folder in the website project. It's actually

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:23.040
pointing at a file, a yaml file, and if we go and have a look at that file, so projects.yaml,

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:29.519
inside the projects directory, this is a file that's written in that yaml syntax. That's the

00:08:29.519 --> 00:08:35.200
same syntax you use to set options in koro underscore koro dot yaml, or in your document

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:41.200
header. But what I'm using it for here is to provide a list of items that I want to have in

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:46.000
my listing. So each of these items, you can tell there's an item because it starts with a dash,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:53.679
I've got three of them here, those three dashes. Each one has a title, a path, that's the element

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:59.679
you use to provide a url. So since this isn't a page of content, when people click on this item,

00:08:59.679 --> 00:09:03.760
they're not going to go to a page within my website, they're going to go off to some external

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:08.400
url. So it could be that some of your projects actually, like the best place for people to look

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:13.599
at is to go look at github, right? This might be a link to a github repo. It might be other projects,

00:09:14.239 --> 00:09:18.559
you know, it's just a slide deck, so you want to point them to where that slide deck is published.

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:24.400
So using these yaml files for listings is a great way to list things where you don't actually have

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:28.640
a page of content on your website that describes them, you just want to have a title, description,

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:34.400
and then send people somewhere else. The image is what's being used in those thumbnails,

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:43.039
in the description, etc. There's categories and date as well. So again, that's sort of what a

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:50.000
listing looks like when you generate it from one of these yaml files, and here I was using that grid

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:54.799
type. I'm going to switch that to table because I do want to just show you a couple of quick,

00:09:55.440 --> 00:10:01.280
easy customizations you can do with listings. So let me re-render that. Now I've got these

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:05.679
projects in a table, and the first thing you might notice, if you've only got three projects,

